Comment: Dear Governor Beverly Perdue: A new Institute of Medicine report confirms that smoke-free policies save lives. The report, released yesterday, verifies that secondhand smoke from cigarettes can cause acute coronary events such as heart attack and chest pain. This report follows an earlier study documenting that heart attack rates dropped 17 percent one year after implementation of smoke-free laws and continued to decline over time, with about a 36 percent drop three years after enacting the restrictions. Thanks to passage of HB2, North Carolinians can expect similar health benefits when our smoke-free policy is implemented in January. Studies like these demonstrate that smoke-free polices improve public health in many ways. In addition to protecting people from lung cancer and other respiratory illnesses, smoke-free laws also help reduce cardiovascular disease, which is the leading killer in North Carolina and the nation. We know having smoke-free restaurants and bars in North Carolina will prevent heart attacks and save lives. Extending our smoke-free policy to cover all workers would save even more lives. As your constituent, I invite you to read the new IOM report at www.iom.edu and consider the benefits of allowing all North Carolina workers to be protected by our smoke-free law. Thank you for your efforts to improve public health in North Carolina. Sincerely, John Jeffrey Carr 2000 West First Street Two Piedmont Plaza, Suite 618 Winston Salem, NC 27104

